QD2_Comment: D2a is a total number of physical polling place locations (651) IN ADDITION to the 20 early voting centers (3 offices and 17 off-site locations) and the 6 drop off ballot box sites for a total of 677.  The D2c TOTAL would have reflected the earlier noted count from D2f (20 total) but that was reduced to 8 Election offices noted in the Election Day voting section which is part of the original 20 Early voting - Election offices.  These 8 sites were not added but merely reduced to 8 Election Offices on Election Day to account for All-Mail jurisdictional sites that are open on Election Day. Each of the 724 precincts is technically assigned a voting location (e.g. polling place or replacement ballot site for All-Mail elections). In certain areas some precinct polling places were co-located (36 co-locations) within the same facility and that is why the physical polling place location total (651) is less than the number of machines used (687) and also less than the Total Precincts (D1a) that exist (724). We had 7 All-Mail precincts where the total number of registered voters within those precincts was less than 25 registered voters. These All-Mail precincts were not assigned a physical polling location and consequently reduce the physical polling place total as well.
QD3_Comment: As a note, we also hired 116 citizen board Troubleshooters that do not serve as polling place board workers but are assigned several specific polling place locations to assist the board workers at these locations with any issues that come up on Election Day. This quantity of additional workers (116) is NOT reflected in the above grand total.
QD4_Comment: Maricopa County implemented "Student" poll workers program back in 2008.  Since its inception, we  continue to realize a steady increase in participation amongst students.  For this 2014 General election, of the 3,848 workers, we had over 152 of these board workers that were "Student" poll workers.
QD5_Comment: Some precincts were easier to staff than others, however the most difficulty we had in all precincts were staffing and keeping Bi-Lingual Board Workers.  The recruitment process for standard poll workers was neither difficult nor easy.  In some rural areas, it was a bit difficult to recruit poll workers.  We do ask poll workers to work outside of their precinct but many of the rural areas were just too far for some out-of-precinct workers to accept.

Indiana law requires the county executive to set poll worker pay. In Marion County, we have a consolidated city-county government and the mayor is considered the county executive by our state's definition. Poll worker pay has not been increased since 2007. Staff believes the pay is not commiserate with the work expected by the poll workers, and even a modest increase would help boost volunteer morale and attract new workers. Despite this issue, we continue our outreach and advocacy to local high school student poll workers.

QD5_Comment: The biggest issue is finding Democrats to work. The other issue is that it is a long day and some older poll workers have difficulty with such a long day.

Because of the heavy Republican population in our county keeping a balance on the boards is what is most challenging. I did have 2 new people that just did not show up. One I called did come in and work the other was visited by a police officer and still did not work. I think enforcing the importance of working is necessary. I dont normally draft for fear of what I may end up with but I do have some stronger language I plan to use in my recruitment documents for the 2016 election cycle.

I sent out letters and/or spoke to over 200 individuals in an attempt to get 55 workers. I ended up with 53. A lot of the comments were that it wasnt worth the hassle of dealing with their employers for the day off  even after I sent a copy of the statutes.
In some precincts it was pretty easy and in some it was extremely hard. In one precinct I only had 4 on a previous year (if somebody cancelled late).

The poll workers that have worked for many years keep coming back but they are in the 70 to 80 and even 90 year range now. It is very difficult to get the poll workers less than 60 years of age to work.

It is increasingly difficult to fill all the poll worker positions. So much of our state and county are Republican registered voters and it is harder & harder to find enough Democrats, Libertarians or Non-Partisans to fill the other positions on the County Receiving Boards.

Recruiting poll workers in the primary was difficult however after we changed our tactics and sent cold-letters to voters in the county over the course of the summer we increased our sub list to over 50.
Harder to recruit poll workers in rural precincts, finding Democrats to work as well as attracting workers in the Primary as opposed to the General Election.
Lifers are easy to get back, (until they age out), but getting younger people to return consistently is more difficult.
Very difficult to get Democrats.
It is sometimes difficult to find bilingual poll workers or regular due to most everyone works and they do not want to take off work.
We have a hard time finding enough Democrats to serve as poll workers.
The parties recruit the poll workers.
The main problem is finding party representation. Kimball County is a Republican County and Democratic, etc., workers are hard to find, especially in the Villages of Dix and Bushnell.

The biggest challenge is finding Democrats. We are a very small county; out of 362 voters, we only have 53 Democrats. Many of those work out of the county and don't want to be on the Board. Other than that, I have very good luck in finding poll workers.

In the rural/smaller communities it is difficult to find people to work the polls from 7 A.M. to 8:00 P.M. due to the older generation working longer into their 70s, younger generation the majority of households both work and a lot of poll workers that have been doing it for years do not care for the paperwork involved with Provisional Ballots or if have to ask for ID, etc.
Difficult to find Democrats.

Having only one precinct, I don't have much trouble finding poll workers. I have more trouble getting rid of ones that should maybe retire but absolutely love being on the Board.They are still doing a good job so won't replace them.
The only poll workers that are willing & able to work are retired folks.
Several workers have told me they do not plan to do it in two years so it will be interesting to see if new workers can be found.

A majority of my election workers are in their 60-80 years of age.It seem like the younger voters are not willing to take a day off and do their civic duty when it comes to elections.I dont understand why.I am not looking forward to replacing these individuals when they tell me it is time to retire.
The biggest difficulty in Keya Paha is to find willing Democrats since we dont have very many.
Hard to find poll workers with the harvest or finding Democrats in some precincts.

A lot of the poll workers that have worked for years are retiring. I have had several younger people show interest in serving. I am going to run some newspaper ads to recruit new poll workers for the next election.

It is very difficult to find capable poll workers. Many complained about the Primary being too confusing due to the Non-Partisan/Partisan ballots and nonpartisans being allowed to request a party ballot. Because of this, we had poll workers say they were no longer interested in working elections at all. Another issue is that so many people are working steady jobs well past the traditional retirement age, therefore they are unavailable to work the elections. We also had several (between 6  10) that called a day or two before the election stating they were sick, had to go to the doctor, had sick children etc. This makes it extremely difficult because even though we try to have a couple non-partisan workers on-call for emergencies, we cant replace that many workers last minute. As a result, at least three of our polling places were under staffed.
Most of the poll workers were the same as in past years. When the older workers decide to stop helping I believe there will be someone to step in and take over.

Most of our poll workers are 65+ and every year we get 1 or 2 who physically work the long hours. In trying to find replacements we find that most individualswe call work, take care of kids/grandkids, or are just not interested.

I have been unable to recruit younger poll workers.All younger registrant voterswork or have small children and do not want to work the 14 hour day.I also had additional issues with my poll workers because after the tornado in Pilger many were displaced or moved out of county.The average age of my poll workers is 75+, many of them have advised me that this was their last election to work.
The reason I did have some difficulty for the General Election was due to the Election workers being listed in a lawsuit filed after the Primary Election for the Dissolution of the Village of Seneca.

We have a good core of workers who really like to do it and are there every election cycle. I usually have to make a few calls to get a replacement for someone who is ill or has some other obligation for a particular election and we have had some who just dont want to do it anymore. So far, I have always been able to find someone to fill in or take it on a regular basis.
The problem I do have is getting enough Democratic workers, as most of the county is Republican.

I had problems this election with my bilingual pollworkers not letting us know that they were unavailable until the last minute. We sent out reminders asking them to let us know asap whether they were able to work. Had to continue to leave messages for them to get back to us.

A lot of my older people dont want to work anymore, but they complain less about the long day than the younger people do. I suppose I could do split shifts, but that seems senseless, since its just for one day. Democrats are the hardest for me to find. I had to use 4 not 5 pollworkers in a couple of polling places.I would really like to be all mail.

Because of the machines I no longer use five poll workers, I only use four, which makes it easier. But because this is such a dominantly Republican county it is hard to fill the positions held by Democrats or Non-Partisans.
I do not have enough Democrats.
A few backed out the week before the election. Not very many people want the responsibility of working the polls, but had some student poll workers.
Seems to be getting more difficult every election.
A lot of work.
I am strongly considering all-mail for several of my precincts and wish that I could do the entire County as all-mail.

We did have to replace some workers; it took some time to make phone calls, but we try to keep a few people trained and on call to allow for these. The biggest problem is to find a replacement worker with the appropriate party affiliation. That is why I like to have Nonpartisans as my back-ups.
With all the push to get young people involved with Elections, none of them want to work elections unless the compensation is worth their time. My Poll Workers average 70 years of age.
If I plan ahead I do not have problems getting election workers. The process is time-consuming.
Some of them are getting very old, but theyenjoy that day out.

The issue we are running into is that they are getting older and many have had to quit due to health reasons and there does not seem to be as much interest in it as there was before. We especially struggle with finding replacements for Democratic poll workers.
The age of the election workers is a major issue  with all the new laws and even if we make as easy as possible they always seemed to get confused.
I have been very lucky in this county.I have individuals calling asking how they can get on the election board.

Most poll workers are retired and/or elderly individuals. As the election process continues to get more complicated, it is difficult for poll workers to handle situations when a voters name is not listed on the roster.
Quite a few of our workers are 70 years old or older and we could use some younger workers, but many are employed full time and not available.
Only older poll workers want to work.
